## Propagating Trace Context Across RabbitMQ

RabbitMQ doesn't automatically propagate W3C `traceparent`/`tracestate` headers. You need to manually inject context on publish and extract on consume.

**Publisher (Service A)** — inject the current activity's context into message headers:

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;

var activitySource = new ActivitySource("ServiceA");

using var activity = activitySource.StartActivity("OrderPublished", ActivityKind.Producer);

var props = channel.CreateBasicProperties();
props.Headers ??= new Dictionary<string, object>();

// Inject current trace context into the message headers
DistributedContextPropagator.Current.Inject(
    activity, props.Headers,
    static (carrier, key, value) =>
    {
        if (carrier is IDictionary<string, object> dict)
            dict[key] = value;
    });

channel.BasicPublish(exchange, routingKey, props, body);
```

**Consumer (Service B)** — extract context and link the new activity to the original trace:

```csharp
var activitySource = new ActivitySource("ServiceB");

// Inside your consumer callback:
var parentContext = default(ActivityContext);

DistributedContextPropagator.Current.ExtractTraceIdAndState(
    ea.BasicProperties.Headers,
    static (carrier, key, out string? value, out IEnumerable<string>? values) =>
    {
        values = null;
        value = null;
        if (carrier is IDictionary<string, object> dict
            && dict.TryGetValue(key, out var raw)
            && raw is byte[] bytes)
        {
            value = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetString(bytes);
        }
    },
    out var traceParent, out var traceState);

if (ActivityContext.TryParse(traceParent, traceState, out var ctx))
    parentContext = ctx;

using var activity = activitySource.StartActivity(
    "OrderReceived",
    ActivityKind.Consumer,
    parentContext);  // <-- links this span to the producer's trace
```

**Key points:**

1. **Why it breaks**: RabbitMQ client has no built-in OpenTelemetry instrumentation — the trace context dies at the queue boundary unless you propagate it manually.
2. **Header encoding**: RabbitMQ stores header values as `byte[]`, so the extract callback must decode from UTF-8.
3. **`DistributedContextPropagator.Current`** handles W3C Trace Context (`traceparent` + `tracestate`) by default in .NET 8 — no extra NuGet needed for the propagation itself.
4. **Register your `ActivitySource`** in both services' OTel setup:
   ```csharp
   builder.Services.AddOpenTelemetry()
       .WithTracing(t => t
           .AddSource("ServiceA") // or "ServiceB"
           .AddOtlpExporter());
   ```

After this, your traces will show a single end-to-end trace spanning both services with the queue hop visible as a producer→consumer span pair.
